<br>
Pretty freaky incident.  This bird is dumber than a sack of hammers, but he felt the quake coming before it happened.  Tripped me out.  No point to this story other than that.  Earthquakes are a fact of life in California, not very common, and very rarely dangerous.  Greater LA Basin will float up north and be an island east of San Francisco in the next 10,000 years, but I won't live that long.     <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=jenori>Jenori</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 86<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(4/30/03 11:32 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1489.topic&index=17>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: So, I woke up to an earthquake ...</span><hr size=1> Yup, Keriru, Guam. <br>
